WEBVTT

00:04.221 --> 00:04.395
.

00:04.439 --> 00:06.571
- Previously
on "New Amsterdam."

00:06.615 --> 00:08.617
- I'm glad that you're up
for complicated

00:08.660 --> 00:10.314
because I'm pregnant.

00:10.358 --> 00:11.837
- Do you foresee any problems

00:11.881 --> 00:13.883
working in a public hospital
system like New Amsterdam?

00:13.926 --> 00:15.885
- The only problem I see having
is getting any work done

00:15.928 --> 00:19.193
while staring into those
amazing, blue eyes of yours.

00:19.236 --> 00:22.065
- You lied to me!
I asked you if this residency

00:22.109 --> 00:24.154
was on the level,
and you said yes.

00:24.198 --> 00:25.634
- I'm going to wait you out,

00:25.677 --> 00:28.767
and then I'm going to undo
every bloated program,

00:28.811 --> 00:30.465
every underfunded clinic,

00:30.508 --> 00:34.512
and everything that you've
built on very shaky ground.

00:34.556 --> 00:36.297
- I am going to miss
this place,

00:36.340 --> 00:37.950
but we are getting ready
for a brand-new chapter

00:37.994 --> 00:40.040
of our lives together
in London.

00:40.083 --> 00:41.954
- JFK, terminal four.

00:41.998 --> 00:44.044
[soft dramatic music]

00:55.533 --> 00:58.580
[UK police siren wailing]

01:02.671 --> 01:05.717
[The Fratellis'
"Chelsea Dagger"]

01:05.761 --> 01:08.938
♪

01:08.981 --> 01:12.768
- [gasps]
Oh, my God!

01:12.811 --> 01:13.769
- Not too bad.

01:13.812 --> 01:17.033
[laughter]

01:17.077 --> 01:19.383
Welcome home.

01:19.427 --> 01:22.734
[rowdy indie rock music]

01:22.778 --> 01:23.779
- No!

01:23.822 --> 01:25.259
♪

01:25.302 --> 01:26.999
- Whoa!
It was an accident!

01:27.043 --> 01:28.914
[laughter]

01:28.958 --> 01:35.878
♪

01:43.015 --> 01:44.060
- Get back!

01:44.104 --> 01:47.194
♪

01:47.237 --> 01:48.847
- ♪ Chelsea, Chelsea

01:48.891 --> 01:51.023
♪ I believe
that when you're dancing ♪

01:51.067 --> 01:52.634
♪ Slowly sucking your sleeve

01:52.677 --> 01:56.159
♪ The boys get lonely
after you leave ♪

01:56.203 --> 01:57.595
♪ It's one for the dagger

01:57.639 --> 02:00.250
♪ And another
for the one you believe ♪

02:00.294 --> 02:05.647
- Hi, baby. Yes!
[laughs]

02:09.041 --> 02:12.262
[soft dramatic music]

02:12.306 --> 02:15.004
- Reed,
about those conferences,

02:15.047 --> 02:16.484
I really need to--

02:16.527 --> 02:19.008
oh, well, you can tell whoever
you're not talking to

02:19.051 --> 02:20.618
that I said hello.

02:20.662 --> 02:23.491
♪

02:23.534 --> 02:26.972
Good morning, Ava.
I just wanted to--hey.

02:27.016 --> 02:29.975
Well, there's a name
I didn't need to learn.

02:30.019 --> 02:32.195
- Hello.
- Adam, you're late.

02:32.239 --> 02:34.110
- By one minute.
As of now.

02:34.154 --> 02:35.807
- What's your point?
- Great.

02:35.851 --> 02:38.288
First up, you need to appoint
the medical commissions

02:38.332 --> 02:39.811
for your
inter-department outreach

02:39.855 --> 02:41.378
the general way that we--

02:41.422 --> 02:44.729
- And why didn't you take care
of this yesterday?

02:44.773 --> 02:48.472
- Yesterday was the weekend?
- Well, you know what they say.

02:48.516 --> 02:49.560
If you don't show up
on a Sunday,

02:49.604 --> 02:51.301
do not bother showing up
on a Monday.

02:51.345 --> 02:53.521
It's--
oh, hey, watch this.

02:53.564 --> 02:56.219
Hey, Mike. Can I talk to you
about something?

02:56.263 --> 03:00.223
Did you see that?
Did you see that?

03:00.267 --> 03:02.269
Oh, God. Max has been gone
for six weeks,

03:02.312 --> 03:04.184
and these people
still don't realize

03:04.227 --> 03:07.752
that they cannot hide from me.

03:07.796 --> 03:10.668
Call a department head meeting.
One hour.

03:10.712 --> 03:12.844
- That's not a lot of notice.
- No?

03:12.888 --> 03:15.151
I guess if they don't show up,
then they are fired.

03:15.195 --> 03:19.242
- Oh, ho, ho! Merry Christmas.

03:19.286 --> 03:21.201
[camera shutter clicks]

03:21.244 --> 03:22.854
- It's January.

03:22.898 --> 03:23.942
- He's here all year.

03:23.986 --> 03:25.901
He's an inpatient
at the psych ward.

03:25.944 --> 03:28.120
It's part of Dr. Frome's
new vocational program.

03:28.164 --> 03:30.819
Apparently he really does think
he's Santa Claus.

03:30.862 --> 03:33.256
Kids love him.

03:33.300 --> 03:35.127
- Oh, God.

03:35.171 --> 03:36.738
- Pumpkin spice,
extra cinnamon.

03:36.781 --> 03:38.566
A basic drink for a basic boss.

03:38.609 --> 03:40.350
- I will not be coffee-shamed
by you.

03:40.394 --> 03:41.960
This drink is joy in a cup.

03:42.004 --> 03:43.223
- I don't know how you drink
that stuff

03:43.266 --> 03:44.702
and still look
as good as you look.

03:44.746 --> 03:46.487
- Yeah, right.
[chuckles]

03:46.530 --> 03:47.879
- Are you kidding? The way
you're wearing that jumper?

03:47.923 --> 03:49.229
Fits you like a glove.

03:49.272 --> 03:50.578
- Oh, thank you.

03:50.621 --> 03:53.624
Yeah, it was a gift
from a family member.

03:53.668 --> 03:56.236
- You should ask for
a few more. You're killing it.

03:56.279 --> 03:59.195
- [chuckles]
Okay, then.

03:59.239 --> 04:04.374
♪

04:04.418 --> 04:06.942
Oh, that's a new one.

04:08.073 --> 04:09.727
- Getting good images.

04:09.771 --> 04:13.644
Singleton fetus,
strong heartbeat.

04:13.688 --> 04:16.908
- And the placenta's in good
position for transcervical CVS.

04:16.952 --> 04:19.389
- It is, but you know
chorionic villus sampling

04:19.433 --> 04:21.739
is never totally risk-free.

04:21.783 --> 04:24.742
- Spinal muscular atrophy
runs in my family.

04:24.786 --> 04:26.048
I got to know.

04:26.091 --> 04:27.745
- Probably a good idea anyway,

04:27.789 --> 04:31.314
this being
a geriatric pregnancy.

04:31.358 --> 04:33.621
- I am a peace-loving woman,
Jan,

04:33.664 --> 04:35.057
but you say that word again

04:35.100 --> 04:37.973
and I'll smack you
with the ultrasound probe.

04:41.933 --> 04:44.632
I didn't think I was able
to get pregnant.

04:44.675 --> 04:46.677
- Baptiste must be
over the moon.

04:48.984 --> 04:55.947
♪

05:01.910 --> 05:06.784
- You know,
this test Linda's taking...

05:06.828 --> 05:10.527
can also confirm
who the father is.

05:10.571 --> 05:15.140
♪

05:15.184 --> 05:17.317
[thunder cracks]
- Message after the tone.

05:17.360 --> 05:18.622
[tone chimes]

05:18.666 --> 05:22.191
- Hey, uh, Leyla, it's me.
Just checking in.

05:22.234 --> 05:25.629
Want to hear how your
VA orientation's going.

05:25.673 --> 05:29.111
So weird not having you
at the hospital.

05:29.154 --> 05:31.635
Look, I know that you took
that job to get away from me,

05:31.679 --> 05:33.985
and I want to respect
your space,

05:34.029 --> 05:38.729
but please, please just let
me know where you're living.

05:38.773 --> 05:41.079
I just don't want you to be
somewhere unsafe because--

05:44.300 --> 05:47.434
[car alarm blaring]

05:50.175 --> 05:52.090
- Help!

05:52.134 --> 05:54.484
- Man struck by lightning
while hailing a cab

05:54.528 --> 05:58.140
now with LOC and severe burns
to his left foot and left hand.

05:58.183 --> 06:00.447
[monitor beeping]

06:00.490 --> 06:01.970
- What happened?

06:02.013 --> 06:03.580
- Sir, you're going to find
this pretty unbelievable,

06:03.624 --> 06:06.104
but you were just
struck by lightning.

06:06.148 --> 06:08.498
- [sighs]
Typical.

06:08.542 --> 06:10.195
♪

06:10.239 --> 06:12.110
- You can't fire Santa.

06:12.154 --> 06:13.677
- Well, the real Santa, no,

06:13.721 --> 06:15.636
but the psychiatric
liability issue

06:15.679 --> 06:18.508
wandering our hallways,
yeah, I can fire him.

06:18.552 --> 06:20.945
- The patients in my vocational
therapy program,

06:20.989 --> 06:22.643
who I vet thoroughly,
by the way,

06:22.686 --> 06:23.992
are far less likely
to be violent

06:24.035 --> 06:25.428
than anyone you would hire
from a résumé

06:25.472 --> 06:26.386
and a five-minute interview.

06:26.429 --> 06:27.735
These are safe people.

06:27.778 --> 06:29.432
These are people that have
held down jobs before.

06:29.476 --> 06:33.088
And most importantly, Veronica,
Dr. Fuentes, they are healing.

06:33.131 --> 06:34.785
- Mm-hmm.

06:34.829 --> 06:36.483
- These jobs are a bridge
to life after this hospital.

06:36.526 --> 06:37.527
They need that.

06:37.571 --> 06:38.615
- Yeah, Dr. Frome,

06:38.659 --> 06:41.052
I'm so sorry, but yeah,

06:41.096 --> 06:44.316
Christmas is over,
and so is this program.

06:44.360 --> 06:48.277
Sorry. Dr. Reynolds.
Doctor--

06:48.320 --> 06:49.887
- Yeah.
- Ah, Dr. Reynolds.

06:49.931 --> 06:52.063
I need you to oversee
the rollout

06:52.107 --> 06:54.762
of our new quotas for
invasive surgical procedures.

06:54.805 --> 06:56.328
- Right.

06:56.372 --> 06:58.374
We've worked very hard to
minimize unnecessary surgeries.

06:58.418 --> 06:59.897
- Mm-hmm.

06:59.941 --> 07:02.160
- Less invasive procedures
like stenting,

07:02.204 --> 07:03.727
avoid unnecessary risk.

07:03.771 --> 07:08.079
- Well,
they also avoid profits.

07:08.123 --> 07:10.908
Dr. Bloom, there'll be no more
sending your patients

07:10.952 --> 07:13.476
up to surgery
for elective procedures.

07:13.520 --> 07:16.392
If it's not emergent,
discharge them.

07:16.436 --> 07:19.351
Insurance companies,
they want people to schedule

07:19.395 --> 07:21.441
their elective surgeries from
the comfort of their own home.

07:21.484 --> 07:23.486
- No.

07:23.530 --> 07:24.705
When I send a patient
up for surgery,

07:24.748 --> 07:26.620
it's because they need it.

07:26.663 --> 07:28.752
When insurance companies
dictate what's elective,

07:28.796 --> 07:31.755
people die, and I'm not
sending patients home

07:31.799 --> 07:32.930
to call their
insurance companies

07:32.974 --> 07:35.280
when many patients
don't have insurance

07:35.324 --> 07:36.630
and they don't have a home.

07:36.673 --> 07:39.241
- Well, unfortunately,
solving the social ills

07:39.284 --> 07:42.810
of the world
is not this hospital's job,

07:42.853 --> 07:46.030
despite what your former boss
might have said.

07:46.074 --> 07:50.121
Dr. Wilder.
Dr. Wilder, please be advised

07:50.165 --> 07:52.559
that we are lowering suggested
screening age

07:52.602 --> 07:57.085
for mammograms from 40 to 30.

07:57.128 --> 08:00.741
- Consider it done.

08:00.784 --> 08:02.394
- Well, that's the spirit.

08:02.438 --> 08:04.788
Well done and thank you,
Dr. Wilder.

08:04.832 --> 08:07.008
Everyone, I know
that this budget squeeze

08:07.051 --> 08:09.010
has been very, very hard
on everyone

08:09.053 --> 08:11.491
so I am so happy
to share with you

08:11.534 --> 08:13.971
exactly what you've been
sacrificing for.

08:14.015 --> 08:18.933
Will you please join me
in welcoming Dr. Mia Castries,

08:18.976 --> 08:21.805
chair of holistic medicine.
[applause]

08:21.849 --> 08:23.590
- Did she just say
"holistic medicine"?

08:23.633 --> 08:25.505
- I lost a third
of my department

08:25.548 --> 08:27.332
for hand massages and crystals.

08:27.376 --> 08:29.509
[applause]

08:31.423 --> 08:35.819
- I sense
a powerful energy here.

08:35.863 --> 08:37.821
I'm just kidding.
I'm not a crazy person.

08:37.865 --> 08:39.344
- [laughs uncomfortably]

08:39.388 --> 08:41.172
[all murmuring]

08:41.216 --> 08:43.435
- Because obviously,
this is black tourmaline

08:43.479 --> 08:46.526
and to get your pineal gland
ready for energy discernment,

08:46.569 --> 08:50.530
you would need amethyst
or lapis lazuli.

08:50.573 --> 08:53.358
Blessings.
I'm excited to be here.

08:53.402 --> 08:55.839
- And we're so excited
to have you. Welcome.

08:55.883 --> 08:58.712
[scattered applause]

09:02.367 --> 09:05.414
- Dr. Castries comes to us
from the university hospital

09:05.457 --> 09:08.591
where she's emerged
as a leader in one of America's

09:08.635 --> 09:11.376
most rapidly-expanding
medical fields.

09:11.420 --> 09:14.336
♪

09:14.379 --> 09:15.685
- Hello?

09:15.729 --> 09:19.646
♪

09:19.689 --> 09:21.038
This is creepy.

09:21.082 --> 09:25.739
- Yeah, just a touch.
- Anyone alive in here?

09:25.782 --> 09:27.175
[door slams]

09:27.218 --> 09:29.873
- Oh, God!

09:29.917 --> 09:33.834
Why?
- Thank you for coming.

09:33.877 --> 09:36.010
- Okay, so you sent us
that text.

09:36.053 --> 09:39.230
- You mind telling us
what this is about?

09:39.274 --> 09:41.755
- We have a shared enemy
who's too powerful

09:41.798 --> 09:46.281
to defeat separately,
so we need to work together

09:46.324 --> 09:49.371
in secret
to undermine her from within

09:49.414 --> 09:52.592
and make sure our patients
get the care they need

09:52.635 --> 09:54.637
and deserve starting now.

09:54.681 --> 09:57.814
We are forming an insurrection.

09:57.858 --> 10:00.208
Vive la résistance.

10:00.251 --> 10:02.558
Now, who's with me?

10:02.602 --> 10:06.910
♪

10:06.954 --> 10:08.825
Sorry, I forgot to say
it's Veronica.

10:08.869 --> 10:10.653
The person we need to defeat
is Veronica.

10:10.697 --> 10:12.960
- Yeah, we figured.

10:13.003 --> 10:15.049
- [sighs]

10:15.092 --> 10:16.485
- Still nothing?

10:16.528 --> 10:19.096
- We literally just heard
you enthusiastically agree

10:19.140 --> 10:21.621
to downgrade
women's healthcare.

10:21.664 --> 10:23.448
- That is part of our strategy.

10:23.492 --> 10:25.450
We can't defeat somebody who
knows we're coming for them.

10:25.494 --> 10:26.626
- Mm.

10:26.669 --> 10:28.889
- Okay, even if that's true,
I'm out.

10:28.932 --> 10:30.717
I have four kids.
I'm not going to risk my job.

10:30.760 --> 10:33.284
I'm sorry.

10:33.328 --> 10:34.590
- Don't look at me.

10:34.634 --> 10:35.635
I got too much going on
in my personal life

10:35.678 --> 10:37.114
to squeeze in a revolution.

10:37.158 --> 10:40.291
- Yeah, and I don't know
you from Adam.

10:40.335 --> 10:41.510
- Sorry.

10:41.553 --> 10:43.904
♪

10:43.947 --> 10:47.081
- What would Max do?

10:47.124 --> 10:50.693
- You didn't even know Max.

10:50.737 --> 10:53.783
- My last hospital was run
by somebody just like Veronica.

10:53.827 --> 10:54.915
All they ever cared about was

10:54.958 --> 10:56.699
"Oh, how many people
did you cut?

10:56.743 --> 10:59.267
How much money did you make?"

10:59.310 --> 11:03.097
Max reminded me that a hospital
can be more than that.

11:03.140 --> 11:06.100
I could be more than that.

11:06.143 --> 11:08.102
I rearranged my entire life

11:08.145 --> 11:10.321
after knowing him
for two weeks.

11:10.365 --> 11:13.455
You knew him for years.

11:13.498 --> 11:17.633
What did he do for you?

11:17.677 --> 11:22.769
What would Max want you to do?

11:22.812 --> 11:25.902
Right now?

11:25.946 --> 11:31.081
- But Max isn't here,
and he's not coming back.

11:44.704 --> 11:44.834
.

11:44.878 --> 11:47.794
[classical music]

11:47.837 --> 11:49.491
♪

11:49.534 --> 11:51.667
- Dr. Clemit,
I owe you an apology.

11:51.711 --> 11:53.800
I've been here a month,
and I have yet

11:53.843 --> 11:56.280
to address your department's
chronic lack of patients.

11:56.324 --> 11:59.719
- Occupational therapy
has a low profile.

11:59.762 --> 12:02.156
We do our work
with quiet dignity

12:02.199 --> 12:04.724
and let our reputation
speak for itself.

12:04.767 --> 12:07.161
- Or we could slap your face
on the cover of magazines

12:07.204 --> 12:08.640
and tube stations.

12:08.684 --> 12:11.469
I'm thinking a full
PR offensive,

12:11.513 --> 12:13.645
community outreach, lectures,

12:13.689 --> 12:17.345
you talking up our hospital's
unrivaled rehabilitation clinic

12:17.388 --> 12:19.347
to anyone who'll listen.

12:19.390 --> 12:22.959
- But that's boasting.

12:23.003 --> 12:25.353
- I should jolly well hope so.

12:25.396 --> 12:27.703
Dr. Grey,
I couldn't help but notice

12:27.747 --> 12:30.401
your pediatrics department
is bursting at the seams.

12:30.445 --> 12:33.230
- The NHS allots its resources
using an algorithm

12:33.274 --> 12:34.710
based
on neighborhood demographics,

12:34.754 --> 12:37.278
and four doctors
is all they gave us.

12:37.321 --> 12:39.802
- That's because
their algorithm is from 1997.

12:39.846 --> 12:42.239
Since then the number of minors
in Hampstead has tripled.

12:42.283 --> 12:43.893
- Can't fight the algorithm,
can you?

12:43.937 --> 12:46.200
- And yet, I just did.

12:46.243 --> 12:50.073
I've hired six
new pediatricians.

12:50.117 --> 12:52.293
- Patient satisfaction surveys.

12:52.336 --> 12:54.948
- Ah, Liz, I've been
looking forward to these.

12:54.991 --> 12:57.646
Let's hear from the people.
[chuckles]

12:57.689 --> 13:00.736
In the States, this is scored
on a scale up to 100.

13:00.780 --> 13:02.956
All these single digits
are giving me a turn.

13:02.999 --> 13:06.611
- In the UK, they're also
scored on a scale up 100.

13:06.655 --> 13:08.091
- What?

13:08.135 --> 13:13.444
But these scores are terrible.
What are we doing wrong?

13:13.488 --> 13:15.577
- Ah. Yes.
No, yes, yes. Absolutely.

13:15.620 --> 13:17.709
I'm just going
to write that down.

13:17.753 --> 13:22.410
Now, I'm going to put you
on a quick hold, I think.

13:22.453 --> 13:23.715
Hi.
How can I help?

13:23.759 --> 13:26.414
- I need to reschedule
a procedure.

13:26.457 --> 13:28.764
- Okay.
- My name is Ruth Gleadle.

13:28.808 --> 13:29.939
- Gleadle.
That's a lovely name.

13:29.983 --> 13:31.593
Ah, excuse me.
Yep.

13:31.636 --> 13:34.422
This way,
Gleadle, Gleadle...

13:34.465 --> 13:36.772
- Oi, while we're young!

13:36.816 --> 13:39.470
- Ah, yes, indeed.
Yes, indeed.

13:39.514 --> 13:44.519
While we are--found it.
Found it.

13:44.562 --> 13:47.043
Let's just take a quick look.
Shall we?

13:47.087 --> 13:51.874
Okay, I see biopsy scheduled
for a growth on your pancreas.

13:51.918 --> 13:53.484
- That's right.

13:53.528 --> 13:56.618
- Well, if I may, Ruth, that's
a fairly serious procedure.

13:56.661 --> 13:57.924
Your biopsy is part of a

13:57.967 --> 14:00.796
endoscopic retrograde
cholangiopancreatography

14:00.840 --> 14:03.103
that you really
don't want to put off.

14:03.146 --> 14:05.279
- Are you a doctor?
- Yes.

14:05.322 --> 14:07.281
No, technically at the moment.

14:07.324 --> 14:11.807
The license is in the mail,
but don't let that scare you.

14:11.851 --> 14:13.896
I'm going to tell you exactly
what's going to happen.

14:13.940 --> 14:16.464
So first you're going
to get a sedative.

14:16.507 --> 14:18.814
It's going to help you
feel calm and relaxed.

14:18.858 --> 14:20.468
Then you're going
to have liquid anesthetic

14:20.511 --> 14:21.469
applied to the back of your--

14:21.512 --> 14:23.558
- Any available porter to--

14:23.601 --> 14:25.908
- [sighs] Grab discharge
paperwork for Greg Treize.

14:25.952 --> 14:27.605
I'm going to reset his wrist,
and then he's out of here.

14:27.649 --> 14:29.520
- You mean Lightning Guy?
- Don't call him that.

14:29.564 --> 14:33.263
Mr. Treize--

14:33.307 --> 14:35.048
where's Lightning Guy?

14:35.091 --> 14:36.614
[soft dramatic music]

14:36.658 --> 14:38.442
- Oh, that tingles.
[chuckles]

14:42.359 --> 14:44.318
- What the hell?

14:44.361 --> 14:45.580
I don't know
how things were done

14:45.623 --> 14:47.190
in the lost city of Atlantis,

14:47.234 --> 14:50.933
but here in this hospital where
we practice real medicine,

14:50.977 --> 14:53.022
we don't just take
other doctors' patients.

14:53.066 --> 14:54.676
Are we clear?
- Yes.

14:54.719 --> 14:56.330
Listen, I don't want
to bum you out,

14:56.373 --> 14:59.681
but Atlantis
was not a real place.

14:59.724 --> 15:01.683
- Get those needles out of him.

15:01.726 --> 15:03.641
- This man needs
his chi rebalanced.

15:03.685 --> 15:04.860
- And I'm a Pisces.

15:04.904 --> 15:09.430
- Why don't you tell her
what you told me?

15:09.473 --> 15:11.867
- I'm cursed.

15:11.911 --> 15:14.609
- Okay, there is no such thing
as a curse.

15:14.652 --> 15:18.352
- I was hit by lightning
in January.

15:18.395 --> 15:19.570
- Climate change.

15:19.614 --> 15:22.269
- I've been bit by a shark
in a river.

15:22.312 --> 15:26.099
I got hit on the head with
a golf ball while I was skiing.

15:26.142 --> 15:29.015
One time, I was kicked
by a horse while surfing.

15:29.058 --> 15:33.889
- When your energy is out of
alignment, bad things happen.

15:33.933 --> 15:37.023
- The man was hit with
50,000 volts of electricity,

15:37.066 --> 15:38.633
and he survived.

15:38.676 --> 15:41.549
That's not a curse.
That's a blessing.

15:41.592 --> 15:43.029
[door thumps against head]

15:43.072 --> 15:44.073
Oh!

15:44.117 --> 15:50.384
♪

15:50.427 --> 15:52.560
- We're fired.
We're really fired?

15:52.603 --> 15:54.518
- Call it laid off.

15:54.562 --> 15:56.651
- So we can claim unemployment?
- No.

15:56.694 --> 15:58.131
The vocational
placement programs

15:58.174 --> 16:00.046
for inpatients don't--
they don't qualify.

16:00.089 --> 16:01.786
- I know I can do better.

16:01.830 --> 16:03.745
Please just give me
another chance.

16:03.788 --> 16:07.401
- Tracy, I can't.
I really wish I could.

16:07.444 --> 16:09.533
- But what did I do wrong?
- Nothing.

16:09.577 --> 16:11.013
You did nothing wrong.

16:11.057 --> 16:13.755
- Sure she did.
We all did.

16:13.798 --> 16:15.235
We have mental illnesses,

16:15.278 --> 16:18.586
and people don't want
crazy people working for them.

16:18.629 --> 16:20.588
Tell me that's not
what this is.

16:20.631 --> 16:23.808
[downbeat music]

16:25.419 --> 16:29.989
- Cheek swab done. You?
- Done.

16:30.032 --> 16:31.991
- [sighs]

16:34.819 --> 16:37.648
[chuckling]
My father would not approve.

16:37.692 --> 16:39.694
- Man, if I told my mom
about this,

16:39.737 --> 16:41.478
it would kill her dead.

16:44.786 --> 16:48.442
That's good that you were close
with your father, though.

16:48.485 --> 16:51.097
If, you know,

16:51.140 --> 16:55.753
this is my kid,
I'd like to be a dad like that.

16:55.797 --> 17:00.758
My dad wasn't exactly the
role model I wish he'd been.

17:00.802 --> 17:05.154
- Floyd, you're gonna be
a good father.

17:05.198 --> 17:06.547
Damn good.

17:07.722 --> 17:09.071
- Thank you.

17:10.942 --> 17:14.337
- And if this child
isn't yours,

17:14.381 --> 17:16.296
no shame in stepping away.

17:16.339 --> 17:18.515
Linda and I will be just fine.

17:22.302 --> 17:26.436
- I mean, you and I
took the same test.

17:26.480 --> 17:29.135
Have you ever thought
about what your plans would be

17:29.178 --> 17:30.962
if it's mine?

17:31.006 --> 17:33.095
- My plans?
- Yeah.

17:33.139 --> 17:35.967
There's no shame
in stepping away.

17:36.011 --> 17:37.708
- Oh, is that how this is?

17:40.711 --> 17:44.193
- You see any other way?

17:46.369 --> 17:49.242
[CT machine whirring]

17:51.418 --> 17:54.160
- Okay, Greg.
No talking.

17:54.203 --> 17:57.554
I want you to take some nice,
deep breaths for me, okay?

17:57.598 --> 17:58.860
This is just to make sure

17:58.903 --> 18:00.601
there's no brain injury
from the door

18:00.644 --> 18:03.299
or from any of your
other hundred head injuries.

18:08.565 --> 18:12.178
- Okay, so that's not actually

18:12.221 --> 18:14.005
going to help you find
what you're looking for.

18:14.049 --> 18:16.182
- Yeah?
Well, call me old-fashioned,

18:16.225 --> 18:19.054
but everything I do
is rooted in science.

18:19.098 --> 18:21.709
Unlike energy work or curses,

18:21.752 --> 18:25.582
or magic rocks whose only power
is in your head.

18:25.626 --> 18:28.846
- Oh, so you're saying they
have a psychological impact

18:28.890 --> 18:31.632
rather than a measurable
physiological effect.

18:31.675 --> 18:34.243
- Yes.

18:34.287 --> 18:37.290
- That's the definition
of placebo.

18:37.333 --> 18:38.813
Belief has power

18:38.856 --> 18:40.467
when a patient
believes that they're healing.

18:40.510 --> 18:43.948
They can and that's why
Greg's belief that he is cursed

18:43.992 --> 18:46.734
is a medical issue and one
that you should take seriously.

18:46.777 --> 18:48.214
- Okay, Greg.

18:48.257 --> 18:51.565
I'm looking at your CTs
and you are concussion-free.

18:51.608 --> 18:53.088
For those scoring at home,

18:53.132 --> 18:56.004
that's curse, zero,
modern medicine...

18:56.047 --> 18:58.311
[soft dramatic music]

18:58.354 --> 19:00.356
♪

19:00.400 --> 19:04.404
- What's that blotch?

19:04.447 --> 19:07.668
- That's cancer.

19:07.711 --> 19:10.801
[indistinct chatter]

19:20.463 --> 19:22.596
- Easy.
Ugh.

19:22.639 --> 19:24.250
- Oh, brutal.

19:24.293 --> 19:26.469
- Yes, Trotsky, it's brutal.
Keen observation.

19:26.513 --> 19:27.731
Thank you.

19:31.126 --> 19:33.389
Max and I were very proud
of this program.

19:33.433 --> 19:34.999
Showed my patients
they could have jobs,

19:35.043 --> 19:38.264
they could have independence,
they could have hope.

19:38.307 --> 19:42.398
Showed everyone else, too,
and now this.

19:42.442 --> 19:45.793
[indistinct PA announcement]

19:45.836 --> 19:47.098
- Veronica told you to stop

19:47.142 --> 19:49.449
placing patients in jobs
at New Amsterdam.

19:49.492 --> 19:51.799
- Correct.

19:51.842 --> 19:54.236
- But she didn't say anything
about them

19:54.280 --> 19:56.586
just getting hired
on their own.

19:56.630 --> 19:59.067
♪

19:59.110 --> 20:03.245
- What do you mean? Hire them
as real baristas and janitors?

20:03.289 --> 20:06.248
- They are real janitors
and real baristas.

20:06.292 --> 20:07.641
- I know.

20:07.684 --> 20:09.773
- You have already proven that!

20:09.817 --> 20:13.255
And who is more likely to give
them a shot than the people

20:13.299 --> 20:15.736
who have already seen
how well they can do?

20:15.779 --> 20:21.176
♪

20:21.220 --> 20:25.963
- You know who you sound
like, right?

20:26.007 --> 20:28.183
- Vive la résistance.

20:28.227 --> 20:30.664
♪

20:30.707 --> 20:34.755
- Okay. Viva, indeed.
- [chuckles]

20:37.888 --> 20:38.237
.

20:38.280 --> 20:42.284
- Hey, Boss, just about
to head out for a spot of tea.

20:42.328 --> 20:45.374
- It's 12:30.
That's just lunch.

20:45.418 --> 20:48.203
- Well, what if I have tea?
- Still lunch.

20:48.247 --> 20:50.205
- Oh.
Tea time sounds more fun.

20:50.249 --> 20:51.424
Uh, I would've
have invited you,

20:51.467 --> 20:53.469
but I figured you were slammed.

20:53.513 --> 20:54.688
As soon as I get my license,

20:54.731 --> 20:57.299
I can take a few things
off your plate.

20:57.343 --> 21:00.868
- That sounds amazing,
but right now,

21:00.911 --> 21:03.349
the patient satisfaction
surveys just came out,

21:03.392 --> 21:06.613
and they didn't paint
the rosiest of pictures.

21:06.656 --> 21:08.310
- Mm, yeah, I know
how tough it can be

21:08.354 --> 21:12.532
to pinpoint the exact reasons
for patient dissatisfaction.

21:12.575 --> 21:16.884
- And yet.
- What?

21:16.927 --> 21:19.713
- Um, out of curiosity,

21:19.756 --> 21:23.194
have you noticed any delays
in your waiting area?

21:23.238 --> 21:24.370
- Oh, yeah, yeah.

21:24.413 --> 21:26.328
Crazy delays, long lines,
angry patients.

21:26.372 --> 21:27.634
I mean, there's a lot
of problems

21:27.677 --> 21:29.331
with this nationalized
health care thing.

21:29.375 --> 21:30.680
You know,
some of these patients

21:30.724 --> 21:34.249
have been waiting months
for simple procedures.

21:34.293 --> 21:35.511
- Right.

21:35.555 --> 21:37.861
So the thing is
Roderick Cantleigh,

21:37.905 --> 21:40.386
who is a knight commander
and the NHS executive

21:40.429 --> 21:41.865
who controls our funding

21:41.909 --> 21:44.738
is coming this afternoon
to discuss my new initiatives.

21:44.781 --> 21:47.523
- That's great! Look at you,
people taking notice.

21:47.567 --> 21:50.047
Sir Roderick Cantleigh
taking notice.

21:50.091 --> 21:51.484
- No, not Sir.

21:51.527 --> 21:52.789
- But you said he's a knight.
- Knight commander.

21:52.833 --> 21:54.225
- What's the difference?
- It's not important.

21:54.269 --> 21:55.226
- Okay.

21:55.270 --> 21:56.706
- But what is important is

21:56.750 --> 21:58.708
if you could somehow
expedite things in your domain,

21:58.752 --> 22:01.320
like, I don't know,
answer the phone when it rings.

22:01.363 --> 22:02.451
Just keep the line moving.

22:02.495 --> 22:05.802
That would help me
greatly today.

22:05.846 --> 22:07.064
- Right.

22:07.108 --> 22:08.327
For you, my love,

22:08.370 --> 22:11.330
I will answer the phone
when it rings.

22:11.373 --> 22:13.549
- Thank you.
- I got you.

22:13.593 --> 22:14.855
I gotta grab some tea.

22:14.898 --> 22:18.772
But not teatime.
Just tea in the afternoon.

22:18.815 --> 22:20.469
- [chuckles]

22:21.383 --> 22:24.212
- Just tell me again
how this is good news.

22:24.255 --> 22:28.390
- Okay, look, I will grant you
that a lightning strike,

22:28.434 --> 22:31.915
followed by a freak head injury
is unlucky,

22:31.959 --> 22:34.396
but if those things
hadn't have happened,

22:34.440 --> 22:37.181
we would never
have found the cancer.

22:37.225 --> 22:39.401
- It just never ends.

22:39.445 --> 22:42.752
- Look, I get that cancer
sounds scary,

22:42.796 --> 22:45.625
but we can take care of it
with a simple surgery--

22:45.668 --> 22:47.844
- No.
No surgery.

22:47.888 --> 22:50.934
- But Mr. Treize,
it is a routine procedure.

22:50.978 --> 22:55.939
- Until the curse makes you
drop a scalpel in me.

22:55.983 --> 22:59.639
- That is not gonna happen.
- Yes! It will.

22:59.682 --> 23:04.121
If it can go wrong,
it will go wrong.

23:04.165 --> 23:06.559
[downbeat music]

23:06.602 --> 23:09.997
This is my life.
You don't understand.

23:10.040 --> 23:12.652
- You're right.

23:12.695 --> 23:15.306
She doesn't understand.

23:15.350 --> 23:18.179
She has no idea.

23:18.222 --> 23:19.615
The fear that you live with?

23:19.659 --> 23:21.051
- Dr. Castries,
can I just have a word--

23:21.095 --> 23:22.705
- You've tried everything.

23:22.749 --> 23:25.665
You say that you'll be
more careful, kinder.

23:25.708 --> 23:30.452
You pray, and none of it works

23:30.496 --> 23:32.193
because the universe
is against you.

23:32.236 --> 23:34.456
♪

23:34.500 --> 23:38.155
- What can I do?

23:38.199 --> 23:41.158
- Get the surgery.

23:41.202 --> 23:46.120
See, someone has to fix your
cancer, and that's her job.

23:46.163 --> 23:50.385
And someone has to fix
your curse, and that's me.

23:50.429 --> 23:54.650
And I'm going to be with you
every step of your journey.

23:54.694 --> 23:56.913
[soft dramatic music]

23:56.957 --> 23:59.786
- Okay, I'll do it.

23:59.829 --> 24:02.005
- So Carl, I spoke to your
former boss in janitorial,

24:02.049 --> 24:04.443
and it seems the only way
to keep you on

24:04.486 --> 24:07.271
is if he hires you
the old-fashioned way.

24:07.315 --> 24:09.273
- Wait. What are you saying?

24:09.317 --> 24:11.101
- That you're rehired.
Yeah.

24:11.145 --> 24:13.277
First shift is this afternoon
if you want it.

24:13.321 --> 24:15.062
- Hell yeah, I want it!
- Good!

24:15.105 --> 24:18.195
- Good!
- [laughs]

24:18.239 --> 24:20.110
Okay, big guy.

24:20.154 --> 24:22.199
- I'm going to learn to draw
your face in latte foam.

24:22.243 --> 24:24.550
- Okay.

24:24.593 --> 24:26.726
- [laughs]
Oh, this is excellent news!

24:26.769 --> 24:29.250
I got some real innovations
in mind for that pasta bar.

24:29.293 --> 24:30.469
- Good.
Good, good, good.

24:32.906 --> 24:35.909
- I tried, but no department
can pay for a year-round Santa.

24:35.952 --> 24:37.563
- You know...

24:37.606 --> 24:40.391
people really do need Christmas
spirit the whole year round.

24:40.435 --> 24:42.524
- Yeah, I really am sorry.

24:42.568 --> 24:44.613
- I'll do it for free.

24:44.657 --> 24:48.356
- Maybe we can try again
after Thanksgiving. Okay?

24:48.399 --> 24:50.227
Yeah.

24:50.271 --> 24:57.278
♪

24:57.452 --> 25:00.673
[indistinct chatter]

25:05.242 --> 25:06.548
- Veronica just deemed

25:06.592 --> 25:10.813
the removal of my cancer
patient's tumor elective.

25:10.857 --> 25:13.076
Which means I can't send him
to you for surgery,

25:13.120 --> 25:17.472
but delaying him even
a couple days could kill him.

25:18.908 --> 25:20.127
- Agreed.

25:20.170 --> 25:23.130
- You said you wanted
a revolution, right?

25:23.173 --> 25:26.612
Well, here's your chance.
Do the surgery anyway.

25:26.655 --> 25:28.309
Defy Veronica.

25:28.352 --> 25:31.617
♪

25:31.660 --> 25:35.142
- No.
- No?

25:35.185 --> 25:37.144
So your whole
"what would Max do" spiel

25:37.187 --> 25:39.407
this morning,
that was all just BS?

25:39.450 --> 25:42.976
- Wait!

25:43.019 --> 25:44.412
If I said yes,

25:44.455 --> 25:46.283
Veronica would see the surgery
on the OR schedule

25:46.327 --> 25:51.506
and shut it down,
but this is a big hospital.

25:51.550 --> 25:56.032
So many other floors,
other rooms.

25:56.076 --> 26:02.822
♪

26:02.865 --> 26:06.695
- Hey. How's it going?
So good to see you.

26:06.739 --> 26:08.610
- I just, uh,
I just need to vent

26:08.654 --> 26:10.394
and for someone to listen,

26:10.438 --> 26:11.657
and since I'm not trying to put
all my business

26:11.700 --> 26:12.919
on the front street
in this hospital--

26:12.962 --> 26:14.616
- Okay.
Hey, hey, hey, say less.

26:14.660 --> 26:16.313
I got you.
I'm here.

26:16.357 --> 26:17.358
I'm here.

26:17.401 --> 26:19.229
- Thank you.
- Okay.

26:19.273 --> 26:22.624
- 'Cause I just found out
that my genius husband

26:22.668 --> 26:25.888
went and got himself
a paternity test.

26:25.932 --> 26:28.978
I mean, what was he thinking?
Now is not the time for that.

26:29.022 --> 26:30.763
Now is a time for all of us
to be focused on--

26:30.806 --> 26:35.245
- Well, well, uh,
maybe he had

26:35.289 --> 26:37.378
certain questions.

26:37.421 --> 26:39.598
You know?
Feelings.

26:41.512 --> 26:46.343
- Oh.
No.

26:46.387 --> 26:48.607
- Look, I--I--I--I know you
talked about us being a team.

26:48.650 --> 26:51.174
- What is this, "I talked"?
We talked.

26:51.218 --> 26:53.655
- You're asking me not to care
about whose baby this is?

26:53.699 --> 26:56.353
That's against human nature.

26:56.397 --> 26:59.008
- I get it, Floyd.

26:59.052 --> 27:01.010
You want to know.
I want to know.

27:01.054 --> 27:02.925
My problem isn't human nature.

27:02.969 --> 27:05.188
My problem is the fact
that you went behind my back,

27:05.232 --> 27:07.887
and you took a test whose
whole point is to tell you

27:07.930 --> 27:09.497
if my baby isn't your problem.

27:09.540 --> 27:11.064
- That's not why I took
the test.

27:11.107 --> 27:13.806
- Then why'd you take it?
- Well, it's complicated!

27:13.849 --> 27:17.592
- [sighs] Well, you said
you were in for complicated.

27:20.813 --> 27:22.423
Oh.
Oh, God--okay.

27:22.466 --> 27:23.772
- Lyn?
- Oh wait. No.

27:23.816 --> 27:26.688
Oh, something--
something's wrong.

27:26.732 --> 27:31.388
- Yeah? Talk to me.
What's wrong? What is it?

27:31.432 --> 27:33.347
- Stabbing pain.

27:33.390 --> 27:36.045
I think I'm spotting,
I think I'm spotting.

27:38.613 --> 27:38.787
.

27:38.831 --> 27:40.789
- Did the CVS cause this?
Did the CVS cause this?

27:40.833 --> 27:42.095
- No.

27:42.138 --> 27:43.705
- We need to test
that bloody discharge.

27:43.749 --> 27:44.880
- And look for ferning.

27:44.924 --> 27:46.360
See if the cervix
is still closed.

27:46.403 --> 27:48.492
- Just--please just let her
do her job.

27:48.536 --> 27:50.886
- I say just start magnesium.

27:50.930 --> 27:52.932
- We got any evidence
of premature contractions?

27:52.975 --> 27:54.020
- What evidence you
waiting for?

27:54.063 --> 27:56.370
- Out.
Both of you.

27:56.413 --> 27:58.285
- Lyn, everything's gonna
be okay.

27:58.328 --> 27:59.373
- Yeah, we're just trying
to take care of you.

27:59.416 --> 28:02.724
- I want them both gone.
- Get out.

28:02.768 --> 28:03.769
Get out!

28:03.812 --> 28:06.772
[tense music]

28:06.815 --> 28:09.557
♪

28:09.600 --> 28:12.995
- Yes, of course, sir,
I will transfer you now.

28:13.039 --> 28:16.042
Well, ta to you as well.

28:16.085 --> 28:17.391
[clears throat]

28:20.263 --> 28:21.612
Does anybody need anything?

28:29.185 --> 28:30.447
[clears throat]

28:32.406 --> 28:35.061
Good afternoon.

28:35.104 --> 28:37.367
- Oh, is it my turn?
- No, no.

28:37.411 --> 28:38.629
I just noticed that you were

28:38.673 --> 28:40.544
filling out your
patient satisfaction surveys

28:40.588 --> 28:41.894
and thought I'd cut out
the middleman

28:41.937 --> 28:43.373
and hear from the people
directly.

28:45.375 --> 28:47.769
- You selling something?
[all chuckle]

28:47.813 --> 28:49.902
- Uh, no.

28:49.945 --> 28:51.817
I'm just, uh, the new guy

28:51.860 --> 28:56.212
and, uh, want to make
some big changes.

28:56.256 --> 28:58.911
- The receptionist
is making big changes.

28:58.954 --> 29:01.261
- [chuckles]

29:01.304 --> 29:05.787
- I have the boss' ear.
So, uh, hit me.

29:05.831 --> 29:10.836
What do you got?
Your harshest critiques.

29:10.879 --> 29:12.751
- Well, it's the same old song,
isn't it?

29:12.794 --> 29:14.927
Month to see your GP.

29:14.970 --> 29:17.625
You want to see a specialist,
God help you.

29:17.668 --> 29:19.801
- Yeah,
it's always a new person.

29:19.845 --> 29:22.630
Makes you feel like nobody
gives a toss.

29:22.673 --> 29:25.807
- And if you want anything
above and beyond,

29:25.851 --> 29:28.418
people treat you like
you're selfish.

29:28.462 --> 29:31.552
- I get it.
- No, you don't, love.

29:31.595 --> 29:34.860
We're all in this room
because we have cancer.

29:43.912 --> 29:47.481
- I'm a cancer survivor.

29:47.524 --> 29:49.004
Two years in remission.

29:49.048 --> 29:52.834
And my doctor was--

29:52.878 --> 29:55.445
she was everything.

29:55.489 --> 29:57.056
When I was half dead
from chemo,

29:57.099 --> 30:01.060
last thing I would have wanted
was to be shuffled around

30:01.103 --> 30:02.496
from one new person
to the next,

30:02.539 --> 30:06.935
so you're not being selfish.

30:06.979 --> 30:11.331
You're just asking for dignity.

30:11.374 --> 30:14.334
- You're a receptionist?
- [chuckles]

30:14.377 --> 30:15.639
Side hustle.

30:15.683 --> 30:20.253
My main gig
is fixing broken systems.

30:20.296 --> 30:22.342
So what do you say
we work on this one?

30:22.385 --> 30:25.258
[soft dramatic music]

30:25.301 --> 30:31.699
♪

30:31.742 --> 30:34.876
- Before we begin,
I want to be very clear.

30:34.920 --> 30:39.576
This is an open act of defiance
against a corrupt regime.

30:39.620 --> 30:43.145
Everyone in this room
is now part of the resistance.

30:43.189 --> 30:47.106
♪

30:47.149 --> 30:51.110
- This might be unorthodox,
but the surgery is not a risk.

30:51.153 --> 30:53.242
I'm confident of its success.

30:53.286 --> 30:55.810
- And the only risk
is to our jobs,

30:55.854 --> 30:57.812
so I need to know.

30:57.856 --> 31:01.033
Is everyone in?

31:01.076 --> 31:06.081
♪

31:06.125 --> 31:08.388
All right.
Let's get started.

31:08.431 --> 31:11.957
♪

31:12.000 --> 31:15.656
- You know, I've been fired
a few times in my life,

31:15.699 --> 31:18.702
and by few, I mean several.

31:18.746 --> 31:20.269
I think the worst time
was probably--

31:20.313 --> 31:21.923
- It's not the same.

31:24.621 --> 31:26.754
- Yeah, you're right.

31:26.797 --> 31:32.064
It's hard to find
the right comparison, you know?

31:32.107 --> 31:36.503
- The suit, the beard.

31:36.546 --> 31:39.462
Being Santa is not my job.

31:39.506 --> 31:43.945
It's who I am.
It's why I am.

31:43.989 --> 31:47.209
Without it, it's like...

31:47.253 --> 31:49.951
I'm falling.

31:49.995 --> 31:55.217
If I'm not Santa,
I'm nothing at all.

31:55.261 --> 31:57.959
- Mm.

31:58.003 --> 31:59.395
Yeah.

32:01.658 --> 32:03.965
I'm not buying it.

32:04.009 --> 32:05.967
- Ho, ho, ho!

32:06.011 --> 32:07.229
- I'm not!

32:07.273 --> 32:08.752
I mean, yeah, Santa,
that's your dream gig,

32:08.796 --> 32:10.624
but if we're talking
nuts and bolts here,

32:10.667 --> 32:12.974
you are extremely employable.

32:13.018 --> 32:14.758
- Ah, you're patronizing me.
- I'm not!

32:14.802 --> 32:16.412
Why would I patronize you?

32:16.456 --> 32:18.762
I mean, unless you're telling
me that being Santa is easy--

32:18.806 --> 32:21.548
- It's not easy!

32:21.591 --> 32:23.158
There's a lot of
hard work involved!

32:23.202 --> 32:24.986
- That's what I'm saying!
We're on the same page here.

32:25.030 --> 32:26.596
I mean, the amount of work
that goes into one night--

32:26.640 --> 32:28.250
- One night?
[scoffs]

32:28.294 --> 32:29.991
It's not one night!

32:30.035 --> 32:31.732
Everyone always thinks
it's one night,

32:31.775 --> 32:34.039
but the prep
starts December 26,

32:34.082 --> 32:37.042
and it does not stop,
believe you me.

32:37.085 --> 32:38.521
- I do.
I do believe you.

32:38.565 --> 32:40.741
I can barely manage
the logistics in my department.

32:40.784 --> 32:45.050
- Logistics, record-keeping,
organization,

32:45.093 --> 32:49.054
overseeing all types
of interesting personalities--

32:49.097 --> 32:52.274
- Hold on.

32:52.318 --> 32:54.189
I got it.

32:54.233 --> 32:55.930
♪

32:55.974 --> 32:59.281
- What?
- Your perfect job.

32:59.325 --> 33:03.807
♪

33:03.851 --> 33:06.027
[UK police siren wailing]

33:06.071 --> 33:07.724
- Roderick Cantleigh?

33:07.768 --> 33:11.032
Hi. Dr. Helen Sharpe.
Thank you so much for coming.

33:11.076 --> 33:13.121
So exciting to have
the NHS Regional Director

33:13.165 --> 33:15.863
for all of London
visiting our humble hospital.

33:15.906 --> 33:19.519
- Unexpected visits
from one's boss' boss' boss

33:19.562 --> 33:23.131
are rarely cause
for excitement.

33:23.175 --> 33:26.178
- Right. Okay.
Um...

33:26.221 --> 33:29.877
look, I know that my
proposed reforms are ambitious,

33:29.920 --> 33:31.618
but I assure you
they are useful,

33:31.661 --> 33:34.273
they are commonsensical,
they're patient-focused--

33:34.316 --> 33:37.580
- American.

33:37.624 --> 33:39.495
Your ideas are American.

33:39.539 --> 33:40.975
- I am aware that there
are differences

33:41.019 --> 33:42.672
between the American health
care system and England--

33:42.716 --> 33:44.979
- Ours is better.
- But...

33:45.023 --> 33:47.068
England shaped me
as a doctor and as a person,

33:47.112 --> 33:48.896
and I promise you,
under my leadership,

33:48.939 --> 33:51.072
Hampstead will be the essence
of English health,

33:51.116 --> 33:53.205
and the community
that I am proud to call home

33:53.248 --> 33:54.423
will support it wholeheartedly.

33:54.467 --> 33:57.600
Shall we?

33:57.644 --> 34:00.081
- We demand personalized
oncology services!

34:00.125 --> 34:02.779
- Doctors of our choosing
available when we need them!

34:02.823 --> 34:05.086
- And you should get out
your bloody cell phones!

34:05.130 --> 34:08.698
- We want it the American way!
- This is a human right!

34:08.742 --> 34:11.788
[overlapping angry chatter]

34:17.098 --> 34:17.229
.

34:17.272 --> 34:18.969
- Dr. Baptiste, your wife
and the fetus are stable.

34:19.013 --> 34:20.058
- Thank you.

34:20.101 --> 34:21.320
- Would you like to
come be with her?

34:21.363 --> 34:22.234
- Yes.

34:22.277 --> 34:25.106
[indistinct PA announcement]

34:36.726 --> 34:39.468
You coming?

34:43.603 --> 34:44.604
Hey.

34:48.434 --> 34:51.741
Dr. Matsudaira said
you're doing good.

34:51.785 --> 34:52.960
- And the baby, too.

34:53.003 --> 34:57.486
- Yeah.
We're good.

34:57.530 --> 35:02.622
- I'm so sorry, Lyn.
- Yeah, we both are.

35:04.189 --> 35:08.410
- Can't speak for Floyd,
but for me,

35:08.454 --> 35:12.675
this ride that we're on can
bring up a lot of insecurities.

35:12.719 --> 35:14.764
[soft dramatic music]

35:14.808 --> 35:17.593
- Amen to that.

35:17.637 --> 35:22.294
- None of it's an excuse.
You needed us. Both of us.

35:22.337 --> 35:25.819
And we were off playing
who's the alpha.

35:25.862 --> 35:27.081
- And who won?

35:27.125 --> 35:30.128
♪

35:30.171 --> 35:33.522
- We don't know.

35:33.566 --> 35:37.918
We told the lab
to destroy the samples.

35:37.961 --> 35:39.615
We got so wrapped up
in that test

35:39.659 --> 35:43.793
that we didn't even ask
about the test that mattered.

35:43.837 --> 35:47.014
♪

35:47.057 --> 35:49.059
- What did your CVS show?

35:49.103 --> 35:56.110
♪

35:56.154 --> 35:58.547
- It came back clean.

35:58.591 --> 35:59.809
- That's good.

35:59.853 --> 36:04.292
♪

36:04.336 --> 36:07.774
- I want to know too
who the father is.

36:07.817 --> 36:11.169
How could I not?

36:11.212 --> 36:13.649
But if we're being real,

36:13.693 --> 36:19.394
you don't need a DNA test
to know if someone's a father.

36:19.438 --> 36:21.483
He's the guy who doesn't have
to think twice

36:21.527 --> 36:23.224
about showing up.

36:23.268 --> 36:26.401
♪

36:26.445 --> 36:29.143
I wanted us to be better
than this.

36:29.187 --> 36:36.281
♪

36:38.326 --> 36:40.372
- How you feeling?

36:40.415 --> 36:41.982
- You can skip the preamble.

36:42.025 --> 36:45.115
You opened me up and you found
that the cancer had spread.

36:45.159 --> 36:46.334
- No.

36:46.378 --> 36:47.553
- Or an aneurysm
or a plague of locusts.

36:47.596 --> 36:51.557
- No.
No, it went great.

36:51.600 --> 36:54.124
- Did I die?

36:54.168 --> 36:55.517
Am I dead right now?

36:55.561 --> 36:57.650
- Mr. Treize,
I just looked at your labs.

36:57.693 --> 37:00.087
We managed to remove
all the cancer.

37:01.828 --> 37:04.222
Margins are clear.

37:04.265 --> 37:06.311
Medically speaking,
you're cured.

37:06.354 --> 37:09.618
- [sobs and sniffles]

37:12.708 --> 37:16.625
- She did it.
- Who did what?

37:16.669 --> 37:18.714
- Dr. Castries.

37:18.758 --> 37:20.803
She said that she was going
to break the curse,

37:20.847 --> 37:25.286
that she was going to be
by my side during surgery.

37:25.330 --> 37:30.073
And here I am.
Here I am.

37:30.117 --> 37:32.511
And you were skeptical
at first,

37:32.554 --> 37:34.687
but you got to hand it to her.

37:34.730 --> 37:36.950
- I guess I do. Come on,
let's get you to post-op.

37:36.993 --> 37:39.387
- [shudders]

37:39.431 --> 37:44.174
You know,
I feel a real sense of harmony.

37:44.218 --> 37:46.089
You know,
like the universe and I--

37:46.133 --> 37:50.050
- Whoa!
- Sorry!

37:50.093 --> 37:53.923
- All right. I'm going
to take you up there myself.

37:53.967 --> 37:55.621
♪

37:55.664 --> 37:57.449
- I'm in the market
for a second assistant

37:57.492 --> 38:00.147
because my schedule
is just too complex

38:00.190 --> 38:01.888
for one person
to handle it alone.

38:01.931 --> 38:04.760
This job is demanding.
It is high-octane. It is fast.

38:04.804 --> 38:10.331
Do you think you are up
for that, um, Chris?

38:11.680 --> 38:14.944
- Absolutely.

38:14.988 --> 38:16.032
- It's only part-time.

38:16.076 --> 38:17.338
- Perfect.

38:17.382 --> 38:20.254
- That said, may call you in
on the weekends.

38:20.298 --> 38:22.648
- It'll be like I never
leave the hospital.

38:22.691 --> 38:24.127
- Hm.

38:24.171 --> 38:28.306
Now it says here that
you worked for Goldman Sachs,

38:28.349 --> 38:31.265
left three years ago,
haven't worked since.

38:31.309 --> 38:33.920
Bit of a red flag.
Why the break?

38:33.963 --> 38:38.794
- I needed to take some time
off to see the world.

38:38.838 --> 38:40.492
- Wow.

38:40.535 --> 38:42.798
Anyway,
this all sounds great to me.

38:42.842 --> 38:45.366
Is there anything else
that I should know?

38:45.410 --> 38:47.803
- Um, yes, there is.

38:47.847 --> 38:50.676
Um, I hope this isn't
a dealbreaker,

38:50.719 --> 38:55.768
but I'll need
December 25th off.

38:57.204 --> 38:58.814
- Hi.
I was paged?

38:58.858 --> 39:01.426
- Greg Treize wants to talk
to you about his chi.

39:01.469 --> 39:04.603
- Yes. Where is he?
- Post-op.

39:04.646 --> 39:06.474
- But his surgery
was cancelled.

39:06.518 --> 39:08.868
- No.
I heard it went well, actually.

39:11.610 --> 39:13.481
- So you're telling me that
Veronica's new assistant

39:13.525 --> 39:15.265
is a secret Santa?
- I am.

39:15.309 --> 39:17.616
[laughter]
- Oh, my God. It's too good.

39:17.659 --> 39:19.226
- It felt good,
I got to be honest.

39:19.269 --> 39:20.488
What about you, though?

39:20.532 --> 39:21.663
This place is
a surgical theater,

39:21.707 --> 39:23.839
it's a revolutionary hideout.

39:23.883 --> 39:27.365
I mean, you almost forget
it's chock-full of dead bodies.

39:27.408 --> 39:30.542
They're right there.
[laughter]

39:30.585 --> 39:35.068
- Well, you know, famously,
they tell no tales.

39:35.111 --> 39:37.070
- [laughs]
That's so dark.

39:37.113 --> 39:42.380
Oh, guys,
I'm having some feelings.

39:42.423 --> 39:44.860
♪

39:44.904 --> 39:48.560
This place feels like
New Amsterdam again

39:48.603 --> 39:52.477
for the first time
since Max walked out,

39:52.520 --> 39:55.305
and it's because
of who walked in.

39:55.349 --> 40:00.049
♪

40:00.093 --> 40:02.008
- [sighs]

40:02.051 --> 40:04.445
- Nothing says I'm sorry
for starting a rebellion

40:04.489 --> 40:07.927
like dosas and chutney, right?
- [chuckles]

40:07.970 --> 40:09.624
My mistake.

40:09.668 --> 40:13.411
You can't help
but rebel against the system.

40:13.454 --> 40:15.674
It's in your blood.

40:15.717 --> 40:18.633
- Well, to be fair,
you did leave a Yank

40:18.677 --> 40:20.635
in charge of a British system.

40:20.679 --> 40:22.942
Uh, you should count yourself
lucky no one threw tea.

40:24.639 --> 40:27.816
- Roderick repealed my reforms.

40:27.860 --> 40:29.557
Every last one.

40:29.601 --> 40:30.863
- Could be worse, right?

40:30.906 --> 40:33.735
- He also cut 10%
of my funding.

40:33.779 --> 40:37.217
- Should have let you finish.

40:37.260 --> 40:41.656
But good news,
I got my license,

40:41.700 --> 40:46.313
so I am now a fully-certified
practicing UK physician,

40:46.356 --> 40:47.270
and I am ready to rock.

40:47.314 --> 40:48.489
Put me in, Coach.

40:48.533 --> 40:49.577
I am ready to help
this clinic in any--

40:49.621 --> 40:52.928
- You're fired.
- I'm--I'm what?

40:52.972 --> 40:54.408
- I can't hire you, Max,

40:54.452 --> 40:58.456
and you are fired
from being quite possibly

40:58.499 --> 41:02.416
the worst receptionist ever.

41:02.460 --> 41:06.899
Today I had to face the fact
that my, um,

41:06.942 --> 41:10.990
my "American fixes"
are not going to work here.

41:11.033 --> 41:13.340
They're not going to work
in this system.

41:16.996 --> 41:18.563
And that includes you.

41:23.089 --> 41:25.004
I know that you're
looking for something,

41:25.047 --> 41:27.615
and I will do anything
to help you find it,

41:27.659 --> 41:32.054
but I have to figure out
Hampstead on my own.

41:32.098 --> 41:37.103
I need to make it work, like,
on my own.

41:37.146 --> 41:39.975
So.

41:40.019 --> 41:43.588
♪

41:43.631 --> 41:45.633
why are you smiling?

41:45.677 --> 41:48.331
- 'Cause I'm
the terrible receptionist.

41:48.375 --> 41:49.507
- [chuckles]
Yeah.

41:49.550 --> 41:51.291
- Terrible.
Really very bad at it.

41:51.334 --> 41:54.816
But also because
I'm in awe of you.

41:54.860 --> 41:58.646
♪

41:58.690 --> 42:00.996
And everything that you are.

42:01.040 --> 42:04.522
♪

42:04.565 --> 42:05.784
- Well, you shouldn't be.

42:05.827 --> 42:07.307
You should be very deeply
frustrated with me

42:07.350 --> 42:10.615
because this whole transition
has been way harder

42:10.658 --> 42:12.181
than I expected it to be.

42:12.225 --> 42:14.793
♪

42:14.836 --> 42:17.796
And I'm so worried that
you're going to hate it here

42:17.839 --> 42:20.015
and worried that you're going
to think it's all a mistake,

42:20.059 --> 42:21.277
and you're going
to resent me for it

42:21.321 --> 42:22.540
what with everything
that you left behind--

42:22.583 --> 42:26.587
- I love it here.

42:26.631 --> 42:28.720
Because I love you.

42:28.763 --> 42:33.942
And, you know,
you're here, so...

42:33.986 --> 42:37.555
so I love it here.

42:37.598 --> 42:39.687
And I don't know
if I'd say worst receptionist

42:39.731 --> 42:41.471
just 'cause there's a lot
of receptionists in England.

42:41.515 --> 42:42.690
- [laughing]
Oh, my God.

42:42.734 --> 42:45.214
- So, you know,
maybe really bad, but--

42:45.258 --> 42:48.348
- [laughing]

42:48.391 --> 42:50.829
♪
